links in the Key: Sources named) --> It is not a list of names of demons, although some are listed by more than one name.<!-- greater clarity may be possible after reading the complex entries. -->\n\nThe [[list of fictional demons]] includes those from literary fiction with theological aspirations, such as Dante's ''[[Inferno (Dante)|Inferno]]''. <!-- the main example Talked here -->Because numerous {{c|lists of legendary creatures|lists of legendary creatures}} concern mythology, folklore, and folk fairy tales, much overlap may be expected.\n\n==Key==\n\nEach entry names a demon <!-- or demon species? all are proper nouns but may not refer to individuals --> and gives a source in parentheses.\n\n;Sources named <!-- 2012-05-21 errorprone -->\n'''[[Demonology]]''': [[Ayyavazhi mythology|Ayyavazhi]], [[Christian demonology|Christian]], [[Hindu mythology|Hindu]], [[Islamic mythology|Islamic]], [[Jewish demonology|Jewish]], [[Thelema|Thelemite]]\n\n'''[[Eschatology]]''': [[Christian eschatology|Christian]], [[Islamic eschatology|Islamic]], [[Jewish eschatology]]\n\n'''[[Folklore]]''': [[Bulgarian folklore|Bulgarian]], [[Christian folklore|Christian]], [[German folklore|German]], [[Jewish folklore|Jewish]], [[Islam|Islamic]]\n\n'''[[Mythology]]''':\n[[Akkadian literature#Mythology|Akkadian]],\n[[Babylonian religion|Babylonian]],\n[[Buddhist mythology|Buddhist]],\n[[Chaldean mythology|Chaldean]],\n[[Christian mythology|Christian]],\n[[Egyptian mythology|Egyptian]],\n[[Etruscan mythology|Etruscan]],\n[[Finnish mythology|Finnish]],\n[[Greek mythology|Greek]],\n[[Gnosticism|Gnostic]],\n[[Guanches#System_of_beliefs|Guanche]],\n[[Hindu mythology|Hindu]],\n[[Hungarian mythology|Hungarian]],\n[[Indonesian mythology|Indonesian]],\n[[Irish mythology|Irish]],\n[[Japanese mythology|Japanese]],\n[[Mapuche mythology|Mapuche]],\n[[Moab]]ite,\n[[Native American mythology|Native American]],{{clarify|date=May 2012}}\n[[Persian mythology|Persian]],\n[[Phoenician mythology|Phoenician]],\n[[Roman mythology|Roman]],\n[[Slavic mythology|Slavic]],\n[[Semitic mythology|Semitic]],\n[[Sumerian religion|Sumerian]],\n[[Zoroastrianism|Zoroastrian]]\n\n{{compact ToC|top=yes|seealso=yes|extlinks=yes}}\nMany demons have names with several spellings but few are listed under more than one spelling.\n\n==A==\n\n[[File:Agares.jpg|thumb|220px|right|[[Agares]] depicted in the ''[[Dictionnaire Infernal]]'']]\n[[File:Chaos Monster and Sun God.png|thumb|220px|[[Zu (mythology)|Anzu]] pursued by [[Ninurta]], [[Assyrian sculpture|palace relief]], [[Nineveh]]]]\n* [[Aamon]]/[[Aamon|Amon]] (Christian demonology)\n* [[Abaddon|Abaddon/Apollyon]] (Christian demonology)\n* [[Abezethibou]] (Jewish demonology)\n* [[Abraxas]] (Gnosticism)\n* [[Abyzou]] (Jewish mythology)\n* [[Achlys]] (Greek mythology)\n* [[Adrammelech]] (Assyrian mythology, Christian demonology)\n* [[Aeshma]] (Zoroastrianism)\n* [[Agaliarept]] (Jewish mythology)\n* [[Agrat bat Mahlat]] (Jewish demonology)\n* [[Agares]] (Christian demonology)\n* [[Agiel]] (Jewish mythology)\n* [[Ahriman]]/[[Angra Mainyu]] (Zoroastrianism)\n* [[Aim (demon)|Aim]]/[[Aim (demon)|Haborym]] (Christian demonology)\n* [[Aka Manah]]/[[Akem Manah]]/[[Akoman]]/[[Akvan]] (Zoroastrianism)\n* [[Akuma (folklore)|A]]kuma (Japanese Buddhism, Japanese Christianity)\n* [[Al Ana]] (Turkish folklore)\n* [[Ala (demon)|Ala]] (Slavic mythology)\n* [[Alal]] (Chaldean mythology)\n* [[Alastor]] (Christian demonology)\n* [[Allocer|Alloces]]/[[Allocer]] (Christian demonology)\n* [[Al\u00fb|Allu]] (Akkadian mythology)\n* [[Amaymon]] (Christian demonology)\n* [[Amdusias]] (Christian demonology)\n* [[Amy (demon)|Amy]] (Christian demonology)\n* [[Anammelech]] (Assyrian mythology)\n* [[Anqa]] (Arabian Folklore)\n* [[Louviers possessions|Ancitif]] (Christian demonology)\n* [[Andhaka]] (Hindu mythology)\n* [[Andras]] (Christian demonology)\n* [[Andrealphus]] (Christian demonology)\n* [[Andromalius]] (Christian demonology)\n* [[Anti (mythology)|Anti]] (Sumerian mythology